Hey buddy.
So the current project is our fork of apache fineract.
we intend to fully exploit the fineract core banking system by creating simplified uis to consume its apis and selling the resulting client-server setups to local microfinances and banks around us.

Currently, I have been tasked with implementing an "End of Day Settlement" process/module/whatever it'll turn out we need.

The idea is that, normally, with fineract we have cash settlement of a cashier at a particular teller  but then this alone is not enough for our needs in our judgement because:
- regular cash settlement can be done at any time of the day
- it can also settle any amount, not all the cash available to the cashier concerned
- the cashier is not dismissed from his position at the end of it. Moreover, the cashier still appears as a cashier to the teller even after the period initially set at their assignment (typically one day long) is elapsed.
- as best we can tell, it doesn't register anything in the journal entries of the system.

The above points are the respects, apart from having its own separate end point, in which the end of day settlement will be different from the regular settlement. They shall be performed solely at the end of each day, shall take away all the available money of the cashier, shall delete the cashier's assignment from its teller, and register the transaction in the journal entries together with any overreach or shortages involved.

I don't know how feasible this is, and there is still a lot to research about it. That I bequeath to you.

My instructions are going to be
- first and foremost, do as much research on the topic as you possibly can online, maybe something like this already exists for all we know.
- next, do as much research in the here and now as possible. what are we gonna need to create this new end point if at all, and what other modules and classes will we be pulling in to actualize this vision of ours.
- proceed with rigour and caution and be sure to request my help with any information if you came to a particularly decisive fork in the road.


